a room all day long alone

44:08.270 --> 44:10.189
telling stories for a living.

44:10.189 --> 44:12.608
- Yeah, but Colin Page is,

44:12.608 --> 44:17.488
he's smart and nice.

44:17.488 --> 44:19.615
He's got a good sense of humor.

44:19.615 --> 44:21.158
He's maybe even a
little good looking.

44:21.158 --> 44:21.950
- Really?

44:21.950 --> 44:22.701
- Yeah.

44:22.701 --> 44:23.827
- I got a maybe?
- Mm-hmm.

44:23.827 --> 44:25.287
- A little?

44:25.287 --> 44:26.789
- Just, just a little.

44:37.591 --> 44:40.302
- And in the haze of
the dawn, they saw it.

44:40.302 --> 44:42.513
"Could that be it?"
Valencia asked.

44:42.513 --> 44:43.680
"Is that the pearl?"

44:43.680 --> 44:45.557
Blake craned his head closer

44:45.557 --> 44:49.144
and saw the magnificent
opalescent shimmer.

44:49.144 --> 44:51.563
At last, they found it.

44:51.563 --> 44:53.816
- It is an honor to be
reading your book with you.

44:53.816 --> 44:55.109
- Papa, don't interrupt.

44:55.109 --> 44:56.860
My favorite part's coming up.

44:56.860 --> 44:59.154
They kiss after they
find the blue pearl.

45:00.864 --> 45:02.449
Do you think the pearl's
gonna look like that

45:02.449 --> 45:03.409
when we find it?

45:04.785 --> 45:06.703
Do you think the clam's
gonna be there, too?

45:08.747 --> 45:10.874
- That is confidential.

45:19.383 --> 45:20.259
- So?

45:23.804 --> 45:24.596
- Starry night.

45:30.727 --> 45:32.479
The pearl of love.

45:32.479 --> 45:34.523
When all seemed lost I
turned my back on the rocks

45:34.523 --> 45:37.359
and I followed the
path of my tears.

45:45.701 --> 45:48.579
Where I fell asleep
for 50 years.

45:48.579 --> 45:49.580
- Busy?

45:49.580 --> 45:51.248
- Oh, (clears throat) hey.

45:52.458 --> 45:53.292
- Here you go.

45:54.418 --> 45:55.586
Soursop.

45:55.586 --> 45:56.795
Native fruit to Fiji.

46:01.842 --> 46:03.552
- That's amazing, thank you.

46:04.636 --> 46:06.430
- I didn't think you'd
ever tried it before.

46:06.430 --> 46:07.264
- No.

46:08.891 --> 46:11.185
- I get the sense this might
be your first time to Fiji.

46:12.603 --> 46:14.730
- You got that from
our first day hiking?

46:14.730 --> 46:15.939
- I got that from the first time

46:15.939 --> 46:17.149
you walked into my store.

46:17.149 --> 46:18.525
- Ah, geez.

46:18.525 --> 46:19.776
Was that obvious?

46:20.569 --> 46:23.030
Malakai, I gotta be
honest with you, man.

46:23.030 --> 46:26.450
I am a fraud, in every
sense of the word.

46:26.450 --> 46:30.329
- Yeah, I wouldn't
say that my friend.

46:30.329 --> 46:32.998
The only person
you can be is you.

46:33.790 --> 46:36.877
- No, there's something
that I have to tell Alex

46:36.877 --> 46:38.504
that I haven't told her yet.

46:40.422 --> 46:42.049
I don't know where the pearl is.

46:43.217 --> 46:44.801
- I know.

46:44.801 --> 46:45.552
- You know?

46:45.552 --> 46:47.471
- Of course, nobody does.

46:48.305 --> 46:50.557
It's a fairy tale, it's a myth.

46:50.557 --> 46:52.017
It's good for business
and a fun story

46:52.017 --> 46:53.810
and people come from
all around the world

46:53.810 --> 46:57.064
just to find the blue
pearl, but nobody ever does.

46:58.148 --> 46:59.566
- No, Malakai, I'm sorry.

46:59.566 --> 47:02.653
Look, look, look, look, I
know generally where it is,

47:02.653 --> 47:04.404
it's on the other
side of the river.

47:04.404 --> 47:08.033
It's there, I just don't know
exactly where it's buried.

47:08.033 --> 47:10.827
And that what I was hoping
was that this journal

47:10.827 --> 47:13.121
would, I don't know,
provide some clues,

47:13.121 --> 47:15.749
some link to my missing...

47:15.749 --> 47:17.251
See he found it.

47:17.251 --> 47:18.669
Well he claimed to
have found the pearl,

47:18.669 --> 47:19.753
he knew where it was.

47:21.213 --> 47:22.548
- Perhaps you have
to ask yourself

47:22.548 --> 47:25.592
if he found it, why
would he have left it?

47:29.054 --> 47:33.308
Look, my friend, Ku
operates a eco-village

47:33.308 --> 47:34.768
not far from here.

47:34.768 --> 47:36.728
About three kilometers away.

47:36.728 --> 47:39.898
His father, Akamu knows a
great deal about the legend.

47:39.898 --> 47:40.857
Maybe he can help.

47:40.857 --> 47:42.109
- Yeah?

47:42.109 --> 47:42.859
- Yeah.

47:42.859 --> 47:43.777
- That would be awesome.

47:46.363 --> 47:49.700
- Colin, (sighs) good night.

47:50.993 --> 47:51.827
- Good night.

47:56.206 --> 47:57.291
- Thank you again.
- And when all seemed lost.

47:57.291 --> 47:57.916
I turned my back
- Night, all right.

47:57.916 --> 47:58.875
- on the rocks.

47:58.875 --> 47:59.960
- All right.
- And followed the path

47:59.960 --> 48:00.877
- I'll see you tomorrow.
- of my tears

48:00.877 --> 48:02.087
where I fell asleep for 50 years

48:02.087 --> 48:04.590
and I woke to the prize
of your bright starry eyes

48:04.590 --> 48:07.968
and saw them reflected where
your love forever lies.

48:11.555 --> 48:13.599
- I didn't know you
were such a poet.

48:13.599 --> 48:16.893
- Uh no, um, this is
the, this is the poem

48:16.893 --> 48:19.688
that Serita's great
grandfather wrote to his wife.

48:20.606 --> 48:21.690
It's a love poem.

48:21.690 --> 48:25.027
And it's, I don't
know, this journal

48:25.027 --> 48:29.781
is filled with, look at it,
sketches, and pressed flowers.

48:34.494 --> 48:36.580
And then you got a waterfall.

48:37.456 --> 48:39.583
- What do you think
all this stuff means?

48:39.583 --> 48:40.834
- I don't know.

48:42.210 --> 48:43.045
It's a mystery.

48:47.591 --> 48:51.303
- Speaking of mystery,
look up there.

48:53.013 --> 48:54.598
I love the night sky.

48:54.598 --> 48:57.267
My dad used to take me
camping when I was little

48:57.267 --> 49:00.771
and I always used to sleep
underneath the stars.

49:00.771 --> 49:02.439
I loved it, I still do.

49:04.524 --> 49:06.276
Look at that one right up there.

49:06.276 --> 49:08.070
Straight ahead right there.

49:08.070 --> 49:09.488
That's Sagittarius.

49:10.739 --> 49:11.615
I figured you'd like it 'cause
it's shaped like a teapot.

49:11.615 --> 49:12.991
- It's a teapot.

49:12.991 --> 49:14.368
- Yeah.

49:14.368 --> 49:17.746
- And right next to
Sagittarius is Aquila.

49:19.956 --> 49:21.541
- You know constellations?

49:21.541 --> 49:25.712
- Yeah, I'm, I read the Odyssey

49:25.712 --> 49:27.964
while I was in 8th grade I
became a bit of a star nerd.

49:27.964 --> 49:29.383
- Uh-huh, I read that.

49:29.383 --> 49:30.384
- Yeah?
- I loved it.

49:30.384 --> 49:31.259
Yeah, great book.

49:31.259 --> 49:32.302
- It's a great book, yeah.

49:32.302 --> 49:34.304
That book made me wanna learn

49:34.304 --> 49:35.597
everything I could about stars.

49:35.597 --> 49:37.557
- Made me wanna
travel the world.

49:38.558 --> 49:41.645
Yeah, you know I always
wanted to do this piece

49:41.645 --> 49:43.438
on astronomy for the magazine.

49:43.438 --> 49:47.234
And what I would do is I would
create a travel map, right?

49:47.234 --> 49:49.486
And I'd start in the
Northern Hemisphere

49:49.486 --> 49:52.656
and I would show you
all the constellations

49:52.656 --> 49:54.950
you'd see as you traveled south.

49:54.950 --> 49:55.784
- That's a great idea.

49:55.784 --> 49:56.785
- Yeah?

49:56.785 --> 49:58.704
- Why didn't you do it?

49:58.704 --> 50:00.163
- Last Creative
Director killed it,

50:00.163 --> 50:03.291
so I just kinda forgot about it.

50:04.626 --> 50:06.336
- It's a brilliant idea.

50:06.336 --> 50:07.629
Promise me that
you'll revisit it

50:07.629 --> 50:10.799
because that is a trip
that even I would make.

50:10.799 --> 50:12.092
- Really?

50:12.092 --> 50:12.843
- Yeah.

50:14.553 --> 50:17.264
- All right then, I'll keep
that in my back pocket.

50:22.310 --> 50:25.897
Well, I'm pretty tired.
- You gonna go to sleep?

50:25.897 --> 50:26.732
- Yeah.

50:31.111 --> 50:32.195
- Hey Alex.

50:32.195 --> 50:33.029
- Yes.

50:38.493 --> 50:39.494
- Sweet dreams.

50:41.038 --> 50:41.872
- You too.

51:08.899 --> 51:11.443
So this is your
friend's eco-lodge, huh?

51:11.443 --> 51:12.694
- Totally off the grid.

51:12.694 --> 51:14.571
Operated by my friend, Ku.

51:14.571 --> 51:16.573
Once was a place his
grandmother lived.

51:16.573 --> 51:18.575
The villagers all moved out,

51:18.575 --> 51:20.619
but she wanted to preserve it.

51:20.619 --> 51:23.246
- What I wanna do is
interview Ku's father

51:23.246 --> 51:24.080
for the article.

51:24.080 --> 51:25.248
- Yeah, I think that'd be great.

51:25.248 --> 51:26.583
This place is lovely.

51:26.583 --> 51:28.084
My friend I've asked him.

51:28.084 --> 51:29.920
- My friend.
- Hey, hey, hey.

51:29.920 --> 51:31.588
- You finally made it.

51:31.588 --> 51:33.590
- Good to see you
- Good to see you.

51:33.590 --> 51:34.758
- Come to see.
- Remember my daughter,

51:34.758 --> 51:35.842
Daniela?
- Of course.

51:35.842 --> 51:37.260
- Hey, good
to see you again.

51:37.260 --> 51:38.595
- Good to see you, Daniela.

51:38.595 --> 51:41.389
- This is Colin, the famous
author of Pearl in Paradise.

51:41.389 --> 51:43.266
- It's a pleasure to meet you.
- Likewise.

51:43.266 --> 51:45.560
- Alex, a famous
American photographer.

51:45.560 --> 51:46.394
- Pleased to meet you, Alex.

51:46.394 --> 51:47.354
- It's nice to meet you.

51:47.354 --> 51:49.272
- Ku, can Colin
talk to your father?

51:49.272 --> 51:50.190
- He's not here.

51:51.733 --> 51:52.943
But he's coming over for dinner.

51:52.943 --> 51:54.402
You could meet him then.

51:54.402 --> 51:55.320
- Yeah?

51:55.320 --> 51:56.947
That would be
perfect, thank you.

51:56.947 --> 51:58.657
- Please come with
me, right this way.

51:58.657 --> 52:00.075
- How are you?
- Not too bad, man.

52:00.075 --> 52:01.117
It's good to see you.

52:01.117 --> 52:02.160
- You've
done some renovation.

52:02.160 --> 52:03.912
- Yes, yes,
yes, you like it?

52:09.334 --> 52:10.585
- Well thank you guys so much

52:10.585 --> 52:13.547
for having us for
dinner, Mr. Akamu.

52:13.547 --> 52:14.798
- Just Akamu.

52:14.798 --> 52:16.007
- Akamu, sorry.

52:16.007 --> 52:19.302
Um, so Alex and I are working
on an article together

52:19.302 --> 52:21.680
about the pearl for the
magazine that she works for.

52:21.680 --> 52:24.057
- Natural Discoveries,
I'm taking the pictures

52:24.057 --> 52:25.100
and he's writing the article.

52:25.100 --> 52:27.602
- Yeah and Malakai
said that you know

52:27.602 --> 52:29.855
a great deal about the pearl.

52:29.855 --> 52:31.439
- As do you.

52:31.439 --> 52:32.691
I know your book.

52:32.691 --> 52:34.651
A fine tale.

52:34.651 --> 52:36.862
- Yeah well, thank you.

52:36.862 --> 52:40.073
Which leads me to
ask you a question.

52:40.073 --> 52:43.451
Do you think that
the description

52:43.451 --> 52:45.620
of the pearl in my book...

52:45.620 --> 52:48.498
- Lived up to your
experience of it?

52:49.499 --> 52:50.375
- I've never seen it.

52:54.629 --> 52:55.881
- I'm confused.

52:56.756 --> 53:00.010
- Ah, how do you know it exists?

53:00.010 --> 53:01.303
- Because I do.

53:05.015 --> 53:07.017
A British man wrote
about it many years ago.

53:07.017 --> 53:09.644
- Right, right, I
have his journal.

53:09.644 --> 53:11.396
Should I, do you wanna see it?

53:11.396 --> 53:14.316
- There is a little known
legend among my people,

53:14.316 --> 53:15.859
about the origin of the pearl.

53:15.859 --> 53:16.651
- Yeah?

53:16.651 --> 53:18.945
The legend of the fisherman.

53:18.945 --> 53:21.364
- You've done your research.

53:21.364 --> 53:23.575
- Wait a minute, the legend
of, that's not in your book.

53:23.575 --> 53:26.286
- No, no, but I mean I
know of its existence.

53:26.286 --> 53:27.704
You can't find it
anywhere online.

53:27.704 --> 53:29.372
There's no written record of it.

53:29.372 --> 53:30.373
It's oral history.

53:32.918 --> 53:34.419
Do you know it?

53:38.548 --> 53:39.633
- Could you tell us?

53:41.301 --> 53:44.554
- 600 years ago, there
was a poor fisherman,

53:44.554 --> 53:47.641
in love with the daughter
of a wealthy aristocrat

53:47.641 --> 53:49.267
who would not let them marry.

53:49.267 --> 53:51.311
One day, while he
was looking for clams

53:51.311 --> 53:55.565
in the Navua River, he
navigated through a tributary

53:55.565 --> 53:58.944
and there he found a giant clam.

53:58.944 --> 54:04.199
The clam opened, revealing
a beautiful rare blue pearl.

54:05.992 --> 54:08.703
The fisherman was ecstatic.

54:08.703 --> 54:09.913
What luck!

54:09.913 --> 54:12.749
He thought if he gave the
pearl to the young woman,

54:12.749 --> 54:16.294
he'd prove to her and her
family that he was worthy

54:16.294 --> 54:18.588
of their daughter's
hand in marriage.

54:18.588 --> 54:20.548
So he put the pearl
in a wooden box

54:20.548 --> 54:22.342
to present to the family.

54:22.342 --> 54:26.596
As he sailed back, the rains
came rocking the small boat.

54:26.596 --> 54:30.058
The pearl fell back
into the water.

54:30.058 --> 54:31.810
The fisherman was so devastated,

54:31.810 --> 54:34.604
he couldn't bring himself
to face the young woman.

54:34.604 --> 54:36.648
He spent his remaining
years searching

54:36.648 --> 54:38.233
in vain for the pearl.

54:40.527 --> 54:43.113
And cried in his
sleep for 50 years.

54:44.447 --> 54:47.742
Over the next few centuries,
the tributary dried up.

54:48.493 --> 54:52.580
And it is said that the
fisherman's decades of tears

54:52.580 --> 54:55.709
now flow over the rocky shores
that remain in its wake.

54:57.544 --> 55:00.547
- It is believed that the
pearl represents the love

55:00.547 --> 55:03.508
that the young woman and the
fisherman should have had.

55:03.508 --> 55:06.052
- He spent his entire life
going after the pearl,

55:06.928 --> 55:09.389
when he should have been
going after her heart.

55:09.389 --> 55:10.390
- He thought that the pearl

55:10.390 --> 55:11.891
would make him
worthy of her love,

55:12.726 --> 55:14.811
but he already had her love.

55:14.811 --> 55:17.355
He lost his faith in her.

55:17.355 --> 55:20.900
The pearl itself
was worth nothing.

55:23.486 --> 55:26.573
- Its worth is what
is accorded to it.

55:26.573 --> 55:28.825
Find the fisherman's lost love,

55:30.535 --> 55:32.495
and you will find the pearl.

55:34.080 --> 55:37.542
Now, enough talk, please eat.

55:38.668 --> 55:42.255
- This looks, this
looks very good.

55:44.007 --> 55:46.509
- Hey.

55:46.509 --> 55:47.469
- Good morning.

55:47.469 --> 55:48.094
- Good morning, Daniela.
- Good morning.

55:48.094 --> 55:48.845
- How are you?

55:48.845 --> 55:49.804
- How are you guys?

55:49.804 --> 55:50.930
- We're doing good,
how'd you sleep?

55:50.930 --> 55:52.474
- Yeah, pretty
good, how 'bout you?

55:52.474 --> 55:53.975
- Like a baby.
- A bit buggy.

55:55.310 --> 55:57.312
Malakai, hey where's your stuff?

55:57.312 --> 56:00.607
- Oh, yeah it rained
further down the island

56:00.607 --> 56:02.150
and there may be flooding.

56:02.150 --> 56:04.903
Akamu's asked me to hang
around and help out.

56:04.903 --> 56:06.154
You two should be fine

56:06.154 --> 56:08.573
to navigate the rest of
the way by yourself, yeah?

56:08.573 --> 56:09.908
- Yeah.

56:09.908 --> 56:11.034
- Yeah.

56:11.034 --> 56:13.870
- Be careful and we'll
see you when you get back.

56:13.870 --> 56:15.497
- With the pearl.

56:15.497 --> 56:16.790
- With the pearl.

56:16.790 --> 56:19.667
Got it.

56:19.667 --> 56:21.920
- Hey, thanks for everything.

56:28.551 --> 56:31.679
- Rained further down
the island, really?

56:31.679 --> 56:33.181
- Seemed believable to me.

56:34.641 --> 56:37.018
They have to do
this on their own.

56:37.018 --> 56:39.145
You know that, Daniela.

56:39.145 --> 56:39.979
- I do.

56:51.533 --> 56:53.576
- Woo, look at this.

56:53.576 --> 56:54.577
- Look at me.

56:55.745 --> 56:57.205
Okay, now look away.

56:59.207 --> 57:00.041
It's good.

57:01.251 --> 57:02.043
- Hey.

57:04.796 --> 57:06.172
Thank you.

57:06.172 --> 57:07.924
- For
taking your picture?

57:07.924 --> 57:09.551
- No, for this.

57:09.551 --> 57:11.010
For pitching the
idea for the article.

57:11.010 --> 57:13.388
I mean I wouldn't have
come here otherwise.

57:15.682 --> 57:17.058
- That's really sweet.

57:18.351 --> 57:19.727
Yeah, you're welcome.

57:29.195 --> 57:30.947
- I can't, Alex.

57:30.947 --> 57:33.533
- What are you talking
about, yeah you can.

57:33.533 --> 57:36.161
- No, I mean I have something
that I need to tell you, Alex.

57:36.161 --> 57:38.538
And it's something that I
should've been honest about

57:38.538 --> 57:40.748
before we even left for Fiji.

57:40.748 --> 57:42.500
- Okay.

57:42.500 --> 57:46.754
- I don't know exactly
where the pearl is buried.

57:51.634 --> 57:54.220
- Okay, but you,

57:55.638 --> 57:59.934
you know like generally
where it is, right?

58:01.895 --> 58:02.979
Are you kidding me?

58:02.979 --> 58:04.439
- I'm sorry, I thought
I was gonna be able

58:04.439 --> 58:05.481
to piece together information

58:05.481 --> 58:07.025
from the journal and interviews.

58:07.025 --> 58:09.235
- If you are just
now telling me this.

58:09.235 --> 58:10.445
- Okay, hold on, I wanted
to tell you sooner,

58:10.445 --> 58:11.654
but then you told me
how high the stakes were

58:11.654 --> 58:13.656
with your promotion
and inspiring people.

58:13.656 --> 58:16.326
And, and, and, and
I'm sorry, I'm sorry.

58:17.660 --> 58:19.037
- Why did you lie to me?

58:24.751 --> 58:27.003
Why would you lie to me?

58:27.003 --> 58:32.217
- I didn't plan on this and I
didn't want to let you down.

58:32.675 --> 58:33.843
For the first time in my life

58:33.843 --> 58:35.637
I thought that I could
be as adventurous

58:35.637 --> 58:39.641
and as exciting as this
figment of my imagination

58:39.641 --> 58:41.684
that I cannot live up to.

58:41.684 --> 58:42.518
I mean...

58:44.354 --> 58:45.813
He always knows that
right things to say

58:45.813 --> 58:47.565
and I clearly don't.

58:47.565 --> 58:51.819
And when you called me and you
offered me this opportunity,

58:51.819 --> 58:53.571
I was scared, Alex,
I didn't wanna do it,

58:53.571 --> 58:54.906
but I was also so excited

58:54.906 --> 58:57.283
and I thought for a
second if I could just,

58:58.618 --> 59:00.245
that if we could do this,

59:01.079 --> 59:02.163
that we could find this pearl

59:02.163 --> 59:05.208
that somehow I'd fix
it, but all it did

59:05.208 --> 59:08.378
is prove that I am
a disappointment.

59:09.087 --> 59:11.089
And I'm sorry, I'm sorry
that I lied to you.

59:11.089 --> 59:12.507
I am sorry that I
wasted your time

59:12.507 --> 59:16.177
and I am sorry that I
got your hopes up, Alex.

59:22.016 --> 59:22.809
So.

59:25.561 --> 59:27.480
I guess we should
head back, huh?

59:32.193 --> 59:33.611
- Colin, Colin.

